<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,310,1781,1807]" box="[189,310,1781,1807]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1781,1807]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="51" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1781,1807]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1399,1827,1960]" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">
The salient features of this new species include: middle part of apical margin of gonostyli deeply emarginate, forming two processes (
<figureCitation box="[636,735,1863,1889]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[235,1340,266,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-104@8.[232,1356,257,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Andes bifidus Wang, Zhi &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862175/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
); ventral margin of periandrium with a sub-triangular prOcess, apical left side Of prOcess with a shOrt, small spinOse prOcess (
<figureCitation box="[1009,1143,1898,1924]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[235,1340,266,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-104@8.[232,1356,257,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Andes bifidus Wang, Zhi &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862175/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3K, M</figureCitation>
); basal ⅓ Of right side of periandrium with a horn-like spinose process (
<figureCitation box="[766,849,1933,1959]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1856,1882]" captionTargetBox="[235,1340,266,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-104@8.[232,1356,257,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 3. Andes bifidus Wang, Zhi &amp; Chen sp. nOv., ♂. A. Dorsal view. B. Lateral view. C. Head and thorax, dorsal view. D. Face, ventral view. E. Forewing. F. Genitalia, lateral view. G. Pygofer and gonostyli, ventral view. H. Anal segment, dorsal view. I. Gonostyli, lateral view. J. Aedeagus, right side. K. Aedeagus, left side. L. Aedeagus, dorsal view. M. Aedeagus, ventral view. Scale bars: A–D, F–M = 0.5 mm; E = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6862175" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6862175/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="51">Fig. 3J</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,324,265,291]" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="7" pageNumber="52">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="52" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,265,291]" pageId="7" pageNumber="52">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[189,1399,311,373]" pageId="7" pageNumber="52">
The specific name is derived frOm the Latin adjective ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wang, Zhi &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" box="[874,952,311,337]" class="Insecta" family="Cixiidae" genus="Andes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifidus">
<emphasis box="[874,952,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="52">bifidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, referring to the deeply emarginate (bifurcate) apex of the gonostyli.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
